# Top Rules for SaaS Boilerplate Development

These are the most critical rules to follow when developing in the SaaS Boilerplate codebase.

## 1. Keep Tests in Sync with UI Changes

When modifying component text, labels, or structure:
- **ALWAYS update corresponding test files** in the `__tests__/` folder
- Update snapshot tests with `--updateSnapshot` flag when UI changes are intentional
- Use `findAllByText` when multiple elements may have the same text
- Use specific selectors: `getByRole('button', { name: /specific text/i })` instead of generic `getByRole('button')`

```tsx
// ❌ Too generic - will fail if multiple buttons exist
screen.getByRole('button');

// ✅ Specific selector
screen.getByRole('button', { name: /delete organization/i });

// ❌ Will fail if text appears in multiple elements
screen.findByText(/demo item name/i);

// ✅ Handle multiple matches
const elements = await screen.findAllByText(/demo item name/i);
expect(elements.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);
```

## 2. Async Testing Patterns

Always use async/await properly for UI interactions:

```tsx
// ✅ Wait for elements after async operations
const triggerButton = await screen.findByRole('button', { name: /trigger/i });
await userEvent.click(triggerButton);

// ✅ Wait for dialog/modal content to appear
const continueButton = await screen.findByRole('button', { name: /continue/i });
await userEvent.click(continueButton);

// ✅ Wait for toast notifications
const toast = await screen.findByTestId('toast-1');
expect(toast).toHaveTextContent('Expected message');
```

## 3. GraphQL Patterns

Use the established patterns for mutations and queries:

```tsx
// Mutations with toast feedback
const [commitMutation, { loading }] = useMutation(myMutation, {
  onCompleted: () => {
    toast({ description: successMessage });
    // Additional logic
  },
  onError: (error) => {
    toast({ description: error.message, variant: 'destructive' });
  },
});

// Always include tenantId for multi-tenant operations
commitMutation({
  variables: {
    input: {
      id: itemId,
      tenantId: currentTenant.id,
      ...otherFields,
    },
  },
});
```

## 4. Multi-Tenancy Awareness

Always consider multi-tenancy when working with tenant-scoped features:

```tsx
import { useCurrentTenant } from '@sb/webapp-tenants/providers';
import { useGenerateTenantPath } from '@sb/webapp-tenants/hooks';

const { data: currentTenant } = useCurrentTenant();
const generateTenantPath = useGenerateTenantPath();

// Generate tenant-aware routes
navigate(generateTenantPath(RoutesConfig.home, { tenantId: currentTenant.id }));
```

## 5. Component Structure Pattern

Follow the established component structure:

```
featureName/
├── __tests__/
│   └── featureName.component.spec.tsx
├── index.ts                          # Clean exports
├── featureName.component.tsx         # Main component
├── featureName.graphql.ts           # GraphQL operations
├── featureName.hook.ts              # Custom hooks (if needed)
└── featureName.stories.tsx          # Storybook (if needed)
```

## 6. UI Component Conventions

Use shadcn/ui components from `@sb/webapp-core`:

```tsx
import { Button } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/buttons';
import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/card';
import { ConfirmDialog } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/confirmDialog';
import { PageLayout } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/pageLayout';
import { useToast } from '@sb/webapp-core/toast/useToast';
```

ConfirmDialog pattern for destructive actions:
```tsx
<ConfirmDialog
  onContinue={handleAction}
  variant="destructive"
  title={<FormattedMessage defaultMessage="Are you sure?" id="..." />}
  description={<FormattedMessage defaultMessage="This cannot be undone." id="..." />}
>
  <Button variant="destructive">Delete</Button>
</ConfirmDialog>
```

## 7. Internationalization Requirements

ALL user-facing text must use react-intl:

```tsx
import { FormattedMessage, useIntl } from 'react-intl';

// For JSX content
<FormattedMessage defaultMessage="Delete organization" id="Feature / Button label" />

// For props/attributes
const intl = useIntl();
const label = intl.formatMessage({
  defaultMessage: 'Delete organization',
  id: 'Feature / Button label',
});
```

Message ID convention: `"Section / Description"` (e.g., `"Tenant General Settings / Delete Button"`)

## 8. Form Handling Pattern

Use react-hook-form with the API form hook:

```tsx
import { useApiForm } from '@sb/webapp-api-client/hooks';

const {
  form: {
    register,
    formState: { errors },
    handleSubmit,
    reset,
  },
  form,
} = useApiForm({
  defaultValues: {
    fieldName: '',
  },
});

// Register with validation
const registerField = register('fieldName', {
  required: {
    value: true,
    message: intl.formatMessage({
      defaultMessage: 'Field is required',
      id: 'Form / Field required error',
    }),
  },
});
```

## 9. Styling with Tailwind

Use the `cn()` utility for conditional classes:

```tsx
import { cn } from '@sb/webapp-core/lib/utils';

className={cn(
  'flex items-center gap-2',
  'hover:bg-accent transition-colors',
  {
    'bg-primary': isActive,
    'opacity-50': isDisabled,
  }
)}
```

Design tokens: `primary`, `destructive`, `muted`, `accent`, `border`, `background`, `foreground`

## 10. Before Committing Changes

1. **Run type-check**: `pnpm tsc --noEmit -p packages/webapp/tsconfig.app.json`
2. **Run affected tests**: `pnpm nx run-many --target=test --projects=<affected-lib>`
3. **Update snapshots if UI changed intentionally**: Add `--updateSnapshot` flag
4. **Check for linter errors**: Tests and type-check should pass without errors

